HE LEFT home 59 years ago when he was 18 to look for work.He didn’t tell his family in Grahamstown, Eastern Cape, where he was going. Now, Freddie Debe (77) longs to go home.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>He worked on the mines in Carletonville and later in Randfontein. He last worked at Rustenburg Platinum mine in North West, and when he fell ill he stayed with neighbours. In 2016, they took him to Letlhabile Old Age Home near Brits. Since then the madala has been begging the home to help him find his family. Daily Sun was asked to publish his story in the hope that his family would come forward.“Our home was at number 37 Mazizini in Grahamstown. I left my mum Nonight and my brothers there,” said Freddie, known as Siguntshi. He never married or had kids.If you know the family, call Mokgadi on 082 626 8049 or Dulile on 083 672 5558.